item.title: Australia’s emissions fell 0.9pc last year
item.description: Australia's emissions fell 0.9 per cent last year, with decreases in electricity, agriculture and transport partially offset by increases in other sectors.

item.title: Coronavirus prompts foreign aid shift
item.description: Foreign aid funding will be redirected to help Australia's neighbours deal with the impacts of coronavirus.

item.title: Zuckerberg distances Facebook from Twitter
item.description: Facebook chief executive Mark Zuckerberg has taken pains to distance his company from Twitter and its fight with US President Donald Trump, as the White House moved to scrap a law protecting social media companies.

item.title: Thorn Group posts $81.1 FY net loss
item.description: Thorn Group has reported a full-year net loss of $81.1 million following the closure of its Radio Rentals stores and a writedown of its business finance division.

item.title: WA hospital visit restrictions to ease
item.description: Restrictions on visiting hours at Western Australian public hospitals aimed at slowing the spread of coronavirus will be partially eased next week.

item.title: Westpac institutional bank chief retires
item.description: Westpac head of institutional banking Lyn Cobley is retiring after more than 30 years in banking.

item.title: Fonterra China dairy imports jump in March
item.description: New Zealand's Fonterra says its China dairy import volumes climbed 10.1 per cent in March after two consecutive months of declines as the world's second-largest economy reopens after coronavirus-induced lockdowns.

item.title: Atlas Arteria completes $420m placement
item.description: Atlas Arteria has successfully completed its $420 million placement, saying it was oversubscribed due to strong demand from domestic and offshore institutional investors.

item.title: UN delays climate summit, citing pandemic
item.description: The coronavirus pandemic has prompted the United Nations to delay until late 2021 a crucial climate summit that had been scheduled for Britain this year, officials say.

item.title: US may cancel China ‘army’ graduates visas
item.description: The United States is planning to cancel the visas of thousands of Chinese graduate students believed by President Donald Trump's administration to have links with China's military, two sources with knowledge of the matter say.
